  "prompt": "When will I start the preparation of ilts?",
  "response": "Okay, let's figure out the best time for you to start preparing for the IELTS. To give you the most helpful advice, I need a little more information:\n\n1.  **When do you plan to take the IELTS exam?** \n   *   Knowing your target test date is the most crucial factor.\n\n2.  **What is your current English level?**\n    *   Have you taken any English proficiency tests before? (e.g., TOEFL, Cambridge exams, or even school assessments)\n    *   How comfortable are you with:\n        *   Reading English texts (academic articles, newspapers, etc.)?\n        *   Writing essays and reports in English?\n        *   Listening to English conversations and lectures?\n        *   Speaking English fluently and accurately?\n\n3.  **What IELTS band score do you need?**\n    *   This is usually determined by the requirements of the university, immigration, or organization you are applying to.\n\n4.  **How much time can you dedicate to studying each week?**\n    *   Be realistic about your commitments.\n\n**General Guidelines:**\n\n*   **Beginner/Low Intermediate English Level:** If your English level is quite basic, you'll need a longer preparation time. Aim for at least **6 months to a year**. You'll need to focus on building your overall English skills before tackling IELTS-specific strategies.\n\n*   **Intermediate English Level:** With a decent foundation, **3-6 months** of focused preparation could be sufficient.\n\n*   **Upper-Intermediate/Advanced English Level:** If you're already quite proficient, **1-3 months** of targeted IELTS practice may be enough to achieve your desired score.\n\n**Example Scenarios:**\n\n*   **Scenario 1:** You need a band score of 7.0, your English is currently intermediate, and you plan to take the test in 6 months. Dedicate 1-2 hours daily.\n*   **Scenario 2:** You need a band score of 6.0, your English is upper-intermediate, and you plan to take the test in 2 months. Dedicate 2-3 hours daily.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nThe sooner you can provide this information, the better advice I can give you. However, a safe approach is to start at least 3-6 months before your intended test date, assuming an intermediate level of English and a need for a 6.5-7.0 band score.",
